	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105003985877?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {Chapter 8 provides an in-depth exploration of STEM education tailored for 2nd and 3rd graders, considering their unique developmental stages, learning capacities, and the core STEM concepts appropriate for their age. This critical phase of education sees children advancing in Piaget's concrete operational stage, enabling them to engage in logical thinking and understand the world more systematically. The chapter emphasizes the importance of aligning STEM instruction with these developmental milestones, advocating for hands-on learning experiences that foster curiosity, critical thinking, and problem-solving skills. A key focus is on the comprehensive understanding of mathematical concepts, where children transition from basic arithmetic to more complex operations, including the introduction of multiplication, division, and the fundamentals of fractions. The chapter also delves into scientific inquiry, encouraging young learners to explore life sciences, physical sciences, and earth and space sciences through interactive experiments and observations. The chapter discusses the integration of technology and engineering principles into the curriculum, highlighting the benefits of coding programs like Scratch and robotics to enhance computational thinking and problem-solving skills. It addresses the challenges posed by standardized testing and the potential narrowing of the curriculum, offering strategies to maintain a rich, engaging STEM learning environment that promotes a positive self-concept among students. Chapter 8 underscores the significance of a thoughtful, developmentally appropriate approach to STEM education in 2nd and 3rd grade, advocating for teaching practices that not only convey key STEM knowledge but also inspire a lifelong passion for learning and discovery in these fields. © 2025 Taylor & Francis. All rights reserved.},
	keywords = {Algebra; Curricula; Engineering education; Students; Teaching; Critical phasis; Critical thinking; Developmental stage; Hands-on learning; Learning capacity; Learning experiences; Logical thinking; Operational stages; Problem solving skills; STEM education; STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics)},
